Introduction ¶

Often it is hard for first responders to take care of all the calls they recieve causing some incidents to have a longer response time. This project approaches this problem with a machine learning model that classifies the accident as more severe or less severe. Not only does this project aim to help first responders prioritize calls but this report also proactivly shows drivers the conditions, locations, and other patterns that increase the likelyhood of a severe accident.

Methodology ¶

For this project the first thing I had to do was clean the columns and put them into categorigal features since there are few continuous features. Here I focused on creating time features such as year, month, day, etc. as well as simplifying the Wind_Direction and Weather_Condition condition.

The second step in my analysis was creating a new data frame where I balanced the severity. This was necesary because severity is on a scale of 1-4 (less to more severe) and Severity levels 1 and 2 have about a million more data points than Severity levels 3 and 4. This is likely because minor accidents happen more fequently, but they have to be even for best resuts in modeling.

Third I graphed all the features that seemed important the data. These fetures are the ones that fall under the three main categories of the data set. Along with this I looked at the correlation between the features I graphed and severity.

Finaly, I built a Logistic Regression and Decision Tree model that predict if the severity will be 1/2 or 3/4.

# Clean wind direction
raw_df.loc[raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='Calm','Wind_Direction'] = 'CALM'
raw_df.loc[(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='West')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='WSW')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='WNW'),'Wind_Direction'] = 'W'
raw_df.loc[(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='South')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='SSW')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='SSE')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='SE')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='SW'),'Wind_Direction'] = 'S'
raw_df.loc[(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='North')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='NNW')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='NNE')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='NE')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='NW'),'Wind_Direction'] = 'N'
raw_df.loc[(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='East')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='ESE')|(raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='ENE'),'Wind_Direction'] = 'E'
raw_df.loc[raw_df['Wind_Direction']=='Variable','Wind_Direction'] = 'VAR'
print("Wind Direction after simplification: ", raw_df['Wind_Direction'].unique())

raw_df['Year'] = raw_df['Start_Time'].dt.year

nmonth = raw_df['Start_Time'].dt.month
raw_df['Month'] = nmonth

raw_df['Weekday'] = raw_df['Start_Time'].dt.weekday

days_each_month = np.cumsum(np.array([0,31,28,31,30,31,30,31,31,30,31,30,31]))
nday = [days_each_month[arg-1] for arg in nmonth.values]
nday = nday + raw_df["Start_Time"].dt.day.values
raw_df['Day'] = nday

raw_df['Hour'] = raw_df['Start_Time'].dt.hour

raw_df['Minute'] = raw_df['Hour'] * 60.0 + raw_df["Start_Time"].dt.minute

# Create a 1 0 (True False) column for different weather conditions 

raw_df['Clear'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Clear', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Cloud'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Cloud|Overcast', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Rain'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Rain|storm', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Heavy_Rain'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Heavy Rain|Rain Shower|Heavy T-Storm|Heavy Thunderstorms', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Snow'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Snow|Sleet|Ice', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Heavy_Snow'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Heavy Snow|Heavy Sleet|Heavy Ice Pellets|Snow Showers|Squalls', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)
raw_df['Fog'] = np.where(raw_df['Weather_Condition'].str.contains('Fog', case=False, na = False), 1, 0)

# Assign NA to created weather features where 'Weather_Condition' is null.
weather = ['Clear','Cloud','Rain','Heavy_Rain','Snow','Heavy_Snow','Fog']

for i in weather:
  raw_df.loc[raw_df['Weather_Condition'].isnull(),i] = raw_df.loc[raw_df['Weather_Condition'].isnull(),'Weather_Condition']

raw_df.loc[:,['Weather_Condition'] + weather]

raw_df = raw_df.drop(['Weather_Condition'], axis=1)

Now I need to simplify the street column. To do this I am going to split all the street names at every space and find the unique words. Since there are so many I am going to filter it to keep only the top 40 results, and from there remove random results such as ' '.

In [19]:
from collections import Counter
# create a list of top 40 most common words in street name
st_type =' '.join(raw_df['Street'].unique().tolist()) # flat the array of street name
st_type = re.split(" |-", st_type) # split the long string by space and hyphen
st_type = [x[0] for x in Counter(st_type).most_common(40)] # select the 40 most common words
print('the 40 most common words')
print(*st_type, sep = ", ")

These findings could be due to increased alcohol consumption on Friday, Saturday and Sunday.

Function to plot confusion matrix

In [64]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Logistic Regression¶

Logistic Regression is a bianary classification algorithm that uses the sigmoid fuction to distinguish categories. It calculates a probibility for the value of y and it checks that probibility to determine its category.

$$ _\theta() = \sigma({\theta^TX}) = \frac {e^{(\theta_0 + \theta_1 x_1 + \theta_2 x_2 +...)}}{1 + e^{(\theta_0 + \theta_1 x_1 + \theta_2 x_2 +\cdots)}} $$$$\text{Or:}$$$$ \text{Probability Of a Class 1} = P(Y=1|X) = \sigma({\theta^TX}) = \frac{e^{\theta^TX}}{1+e^{\theta^TX}} $$

First we need to build our model to the best availible parameters. After we build the model, we fit it with the training feature set and result set inorder to teach the model.

In [69]:
LR = LogisticRegression(C=1, 
                         solver='saga', 
                         random_state=42,
                         max_iter = 10000,
                         penalty = 'l1').fit(X_train,y_train)

Jaccard index¶

Lets try jaccard index for accuracy evaluation. we can define jaccard as the size of the intersection divided by the size of the union of two label sets. If the entire set of predicted labels for a sample strictly match with the true set of labels, then the subset accuracy is 1.0; otherwise it is 0.0.

In [73]:
LR_js = jaccard_score(y_test, yhat)
print("Jaccard Score: ", LR_js)

Jaccard Score:  0.588180815007488

Log loss¶

Now, lets try log loss for evaluation. In logistic regression, the output can be the probability of 3/4 severity accident (or equals to 1). This probability is a value between 0 and 1. Log loss (Logarithmic loss) measures the performance of a classifier where the predicted output is a probability value between 0 and 1.

In [74]:
LR_ll = log_loss(y_test, yhat_prob)
print("Log Loss Score: ", LR_ll)

Log Loss Score:  0.5381339892611274

Results & Discussion¶

Unfortunatly, my classification models arent accurate; however given more time I would be able to drasticly imporove them. I think I could select features for the model better relating to their correlation but I did not have the time.

Our exploratory analysis showed really interesting trends with the data. I was not expecting time so correlate with severity. There were many obvious trends on all the graphs relating to time and it is something worth exploring more. On the other hand, I was supprised by how little of a true corelation there was between the weather conditions and severity, but again, I need to spend more time exploring.

Conclusion ¶

My objective in this project was to be able to predict severity off of the features in this data and I wasnt able to do that with the level of confidence I would like. However, this is still a helpful project for all the resons I wanted. This will give first responders an idea of the urgency of a call and it can help show drivers when and where it is safe to drive.
